b1ac4cda-244d-4cfe-ada2-98d0029e4352.09aa4c45-1ada-43f8-be27-83cafa8023fd.description=Description\:
 
 This step will cluster enable your standby database so it can belong to a RAC enviroment.
 
 Dependencies\: Run as instance owner.
 
 Return Code\:
 
 0 \= Step ran successfully.
 1 \= Step failed.

Inputs\:
 command - executes ClusterEnableStandbyDatabasev2.py
 DB Unique Name - Required\: Target Database Unique Name across Cluster Nodes.
 Env Type - Type of Oracle environment currently used. (GRID_CLUSTER, GRID_STANDALONE, STANDALONE)
 Instance Wrapper - Optional\: Jython call wrapper to run as the Oracle Instance owner.
 Oracle Account - Required\: Owner of the Oracle database software.
 Oracle Home - Required\: Primary Software directory of the Oracle Software installation.
 Oracle OS User - Required\: Oracle OS username used to derive primary node database properties.
 Oracle SID - Required\: Database instance, also known as SID.
 Oracle sys Password - Required\: SYS Password for the primary and secondary databases.
 Standby DB Prefix - Required\: Prefix that is appended to the DB_NAME to become the DB_UNIQUE_NAME for the standby databases.
 Standby Node Hostnames - Required\: Comma-separated list of up to 30 standby database server host names or IP addresses. If more than one IP address/hostname is entered, it indicates that the standby database is on RAC. Specify the hostnames (node1, node2, node3, etc.).
 host - Target to run this command against
 password - Login information for host
 username - Login information for host
 protocol - ssh/wmi
 timeout - Time (ms) before auto-exit\: use ${ExtendedTimeout} to lengthen.

Results\:
 Exit Code - Exit code of the step needed for branching.

 b1ac4cda-244d-4cfe-ada2-98d0029e4352.14e6e188-e330-4cf5-b563-6be82c10b2ba.description=a880432a-0afc-413a-8b4c-479da204e83b.a09a5501-aae7-4a08-80bb-4e902bfe2bb8.description b1ac4cda-244d-4cfe-ada2-98d0029e4352.1d5e8ab9-eeec-45c3-b855-948b718e01f7.description=Description\:
 
 This step will configurate the initialization parameters for the target database to support Data Guard. 
 
 Dependencies\: Run as instance owner.
 
 Return Code\:
 
 0 \= Step ran successfully.
 1 \= Step failed.

Inputs\:
 command - executes SetDataGuardPrimaryDBInitializationParametersv2.py
 Archive Lag Target - Optional\: For Provision Oracle Data Guard task. Specifies the maximum time (in seconds) by which the standby database can lag behind the primary database. Valid values are 0 (zero) or 60-7200 seconds. If you specify Archive Lag Target, you must also specify the Standby DB Unique Name.
 ASM Disk Group - Optional\: ASM (Automatic Storage Management) Disk group where the data files are located for the target database. This is not required for Standalone Data Guard. This is required for RAC environments.
 Bounce Primary - Required\: Set to True if the primary database will be restarted. Otherwise set to False.
 Change Remote Login Passwordfile - Optional\: Set to Yes if HP DMA is permitted to change the value of the Remote_Login_Passwordfile init.ora parameter to EXCLUSIVE (if it is not already set to EXCLUSIVE on the primary database). The default is Yes.
 Database Protection Mode - Required\: Data Guard database protection mode. Valid values are Maximum Performance (transactions commit after the redo data required to recover those transactions is written to the online redo log), Maximum Availability (transactions commit after the redo data is written to the online redo log and the standby redo log on at least one synchronized standby database), and Maximum Protection (similar to Maximum Availability, except that the primary database shuts down if it cannot write its redo stream to at least one synchronized standby database).
 Datafile Location - Required\: Location of the target database datafiles.
 DB Unique Name - Optional\: Target Database Unique Name across Cluster Nodes. If empty, it will be set to the Primary Instance Name.
 Derived Log Archive Dest1 - Required\: Location of the archive logs for the target database.
 Env Type - Type of Oracle environment currently used. (GRID_CLUSTER, GRID_STANDALONE, STANDALONE)
 Instance Wrapper - Optional\: Jython call wrapper to run as the Oracle Instance owner.
 Log Archive Dest 1 - Optional\: The target destination for the archived logfiles on the primary database (if it is not already set in the primary database). The default is none.
 Oracle Home - Required\: Primary Software directory of the Oracle Software installation.
 Oracle SID - Required\: Database instance, also known as SID.
 Oracle Version - Version of Oracle installed on target machine.
 Primary Database Name - Required\: The shared database name. This is obtained from the metadata.
 Remote Login Passwordfile - Optional\: The mode for the remote password file. Valid values are SHARED and EXCLUSIVE. If using EXCLUSIVE mode, the Change Remote Login Passwordfile must be set to Yes.
 Standby DB Prefix Name - Required\: Prefix that is appended to the DB_NAME to become the DB_UNIQUE_NAME for the standby databases.
 host - Target to run this command against
 password - Login information for host
 username - Login information for host
 protocol - ssh/wmi
 timeout - Time (ms) before auto-exit\: use ${ExtendedTimeout} to lengthen.

Results\:
 Bounce Primary - Set to True if the primary database will be restarted. Otherwise set to False.
 DB Unique Name - Target Database Unique Name across Cluster Nodes. If empty, it will be set to the Primary Instance Name.
 Log Archive Dest 1 - The target destination for the archived logfiles on the primary database (if it is not already set in the primary database). The default is none.
 Log Archive Dest 1 Location - Location of the archive logs for the primary database.
 Exit Code - Exit code of the step needed for branching.

 b1ac4cda-244d-4cfe-ada2-98d0029e4352.434fb6da-db95-48c9-a1da-26a6f7152136.description=Description\:
 
 This step uses RMAN to duplicate a primary database to a standby database location that has already been prepared. 
 
 Dependencies\: Run as the Server Wrapper
 Standby database need to be already created and running in a nomount mode.
 
 Return Code\:
 
 0 \= Step ran successfully.
 1 \= Step failed.

Inputs\:
 command - executes RunRMANDuplicatewithStandbyInitParametersv4.py
 Archive Lag Target - Required\: Set to True if the database has Archive Logging turned one. Otherwise set to False.
 ASM Disk Group - Required\: ASM (Automatic Storage Management) Disk group where the data files are located for the target database. This is not required for Standalone Data Guard. This is required for RAC environments.
 Audit File Dest - Required\: Location of target database audit file.
 DB File Name Convert - Optional\: Used only if the primary and standby database datafiles will reside in different locations on the respective servers. Specify an even number of strings\: "string1","string2","string3", "string4",... where string 1 is a sequence of characters in the primary database datafile name, string 2 is a sequence of characters in the first standby database datafile name, string 3 is a sequence of characters in the second primary database datafile name, string 4 is a sequence of characters in the second standby database datafile name, and so on. Each string must be delimited with single or double quotes. For example\: "newyork","chicago","newyork", "atlanta".
 DB Unique Name - Required\: Target Database Unique Name across Cluster Nodes.
 Env Type - Type of Oracle environment currently used. (GRID_CLUSTER, GRID_STANDALONE, STANDALONE)
 Instance Wrapper - String to execute routine as an instance superuser.
 Log Archive Dest 1 - Optional\: The target destination for the archived logfiles on the primary database (if it is not already set in the primary database). The default is none.
 Log Archive Dest 1 Location - Optional\: Location of the archive logs for the primary database.
 Log File Name Convert - Optional\: Used only if the primary and standby redo log files will reside in different locations on the respective servers. Specify an even number of strings\: "string1","string2","string3", "string4",... where string 1 is a sequence of characters in the primary database redo log file name, string 2 is a sequence of characters in the first standby database redo log file name, string 3 is a sequence of characters in the second primary database redo log file name, string 4 is a sequence of characters in the second standby database redo log file name, and so on. Each string must be delimited with single or double quotes. For example\: "newyork","chicago","newyork", "atlanta".
 Number of RMAN Auxiliary Channels - Optional\: Number of RMAN (Recovery Manger) auxiliary channels to be used during the RMAN duplicate database process. The default is 2.
 Number of RMAN Primary Channels - Optional\: Number of RMAN (Recovery Manger) primary channels to be used during the RMAN duplicate database process. The default is 2.
 Oracle Home - Required\: Primary Software directory of the Oracle Software installation.
 Oracle OS User - Required\: Oracle OS username used to derive primary node database properties.
 Oracle SID - Required\: Database instance, also known as SID.
 Oracle sys Password - Required\: SYS Password for the primary and secondary databases.
 Oracle Version - Version of Oracle on Target
 Oratab File Location - Optional\: Fully-qualified path to the oratab file. The default is /etc/oratab
 Primary Controlfile Location - Required\: Location of the control files on the primary database.
 Primary Node Hostnames - Required\: Comma-separated list of primary database server host names or IP addresses. If more than one IP address/hostname is entered, it indicates that the primary database is on RAC. Specify the hostnames (node1, node2, node3, etc.).
 Remote Listener - Required\: Listener name and port on the standby database. For example\: LISTENER\:1521
 Server Wrapper - Optional\: Jython call wrapper to run as the admin user.
 Standby DB Prefix - Required\: Prefix that is appended to the DB_NAME to become the DB_UNIQUE_NAME for the standby databases.
 Standby Node Hostnames - Required\: Comma-separated list of up to 30 standby database server host names or IP addresses. If more than one IP address/hostname is entered, it indicates that the standby database is on RAC. Specify the hostnames (node1, node2, node3, etc.).
 host - Target to run this command against
 password - Login information for host
 username - Login information for host
 protocol - ssh/wmi
 timeout - Time (ms) before auto-exit\: use ${ExtendedTimeout} to lengthen.

Results\:
 Standby Controlfile Location - Location of the control files on the standby database.
 Exit Code - Exit code of the step needed for branching.
 b1ac4cda-244d-4cfe-ada2-98d0029e4352.4b339176-a725-46ca-be5c-4b45aa144290.description=Description\:
 
To further validate the primary database and confirm its Data Guard readiness, this step collects, validates, and stores the following database attributes. Most of these attributes will also be used for generating initialization parameters when building the standby database. The ${Primary DB Instance Name} (otherwise known as SID) must be used to connect to the database instance. 

 o - Cluster Database
 o - LogMode
 o - Protection Mode
 o - DB_Unique_Name
 o - DB_Name
 o - Force_Logging
 o - DG_Broker_Start
 o - Remote_Login_Passwordfile
 o - Log_archive_dest_1
 o - Spfile
 o - Controlfiles
 o - Count Online Redo Logs
 o - Average Online Redo Log Size
 o - Logfile Location
 
Dependencies\: Run as instance owner.
 
Return Code\:

0 \= Step ran successfully.
1 \= Step failed.

 b1ac4cda-244d-4cfe-ada2-98d0029e4352.description=<pre>
 Purpose

This workflow enables you to provision the Standby database for an already provisioned standby host and ORACLE_HOME and then to set up Data Guard. 


 Dependencies

This workflow requires Oracle Database Enterprise Edition version 11.2 (or later). It assumes that the primary database is already provisioned and running and the standby host is available with an RDBMS ORACLE_HOME provisioned. These can be met with workflows Provision Oracle Home and Provision an Oracle Database.

This workflow also requires root and oracle user ID equivalence across all primary and standby database servers represented in the Data Guard setup.This workflow will regenerate the RSA keys for the Oracle user, setup passwordless SSH login, and add the details of all nodes on all the nodes in /etc/hosts file.

Root and oracle userid equivalence must exist between the nodes in the Primary RAC and the nodes in the Standby RAC. The use of this workflow is only supported in an Oracle 11.2 environment.

 Usage Instructions

Review the input parameters listed below, and create a deployment using values appropriate for your environment. This workflow is intended to be run on the standby host (in a non-RAC environment) or the first of multiple standby nodes in a RAC environment.

 Required Inputs

 Server Target - The desired target to run this flow against.
 Server Target Username - The user to login to the Server Target as.
 Server Target Password - The password to login as the Server Target Username.
 Download Source Host - The target host where the files needed for this flow can be downloaded from.
 Download Source Path - The path to where the files can be found on the Download Source Host.
 Database Protection Mode - Required\: Data Guard database protection mode. Valid values are Maximum Performance (transactions commit after the redo data required to recover those transactions is written to the online redo log), Maximum Availability (transactions commit after the redo data is written to the online redo log and the standby redo log on at least one synchronized standby database), and Maximum Protection (similar to Maximum Availability, except that the primary database shuts down if it cannot write its redo stream to at least one synchronized standby database).
 Database.Name - No description
 Instance.Name - No description
 Oracle OS User - Required\: Oracle OS username used to derive primary node database properties.
 Oracle sys Password - Required\: SYS Password for the primary and secondary databases.
 Primary Node Hostnames - Required\: Comma-separated list of primary database server host names or IP addresses. If more than one IP address/hostname is entered, it indicates that the primary database is on RAC. Specify the hostnames (node1, node2, node3, etc.).
 Server.Become Routine - No description
 Server.Name - No description
 Standby DB Prefix Name - Required\: Prefix that is appended to the DB_NAME to become the DB_UNIQUE_NAME for the standby databases.
 Standby Node Hostnames - Required\: Comma-separated list of up to 30 standby database server host names or IP addresses. If more than one IP address/hostname is entered, it indicates that the standby database is on RAC. Specify the hostnames (node1, node2, node3, etc.).

 Optional Inputs

 Clean Code Base - Remove code base from target after execution (True || False).
 Clean JRE - Remove JRE from target after execution (True || False).
 Debug Level - Set level of output [(least) 1-5 (most)]
 Oratab File Location - Optional\: Fully-qualified path to the oratab file. The default is /etc/oratab
 Location for Controlfiles on Standby Server - Optional\: Comma-separated list of fully-qualified controlfile filenames to create multiple copies of the controlfile on the standby database. By default, only one controlfile is generated on the standby database. The paths must already exist on the target servers.
 Change Remote Login PasswordFile on Primary - Optional\: Set to Yes if HP DMA is permitted to change the value of the Remote_Login_Passwordfile init.ora parameter to EXCLUSIVE (if it is not already set to EXCLUSIVE on the primary database). The default is Yes.
 Number of RMAN Auxiliary Channels - Optional\: Number of RMAN (Recovery Manger) auxiliary channels to be used during the RMAN duplicate database process.
 Log Archive Dest 1 - Optional\: The target destination for the archived logfiles on the primary database (if it is not already set in the primary database). The default is none.
 Archive Lag Target - Optional\: Specifies the maximum time (in seconds) by which the standby database can lag behind the primary database. Valid values are 0 (zero) or 60-7200 seconds. If you specify Archive Lag Target, you must also specify the Standby DB Unique Name.
 Primary DB Listener Port Number - Optional\: Port number for the primary database listener. The default is the Oracle default.
 Log File Name Convert - Optional\: Used only if the primary and standby redo log files will reside in different locations on the respective servers. Specify an even number of strings\: "string1","string2","string3", "string4",... where string 1 is a sequence of characters in the primary database redo log file name, string 2 is a sequence of characters in the first standby database redo log file name, string 3 is a sequence of characters in the second primary database redo log file name, string 4 is a sequence of characters in the second standby database redo log file name, and so on. Each string must be delimited with single or double quotes. For example\: "newyork","chicago","newyork", "atlanta".
 Tnsnames File Location - Optional\: Fully-qualified filename for the TNS (Transparent Network Substrate) file. This is only needed for non-standard installs. Do not specify if using the default file $ORACLE_HOME/network/admin/tnsnames.ora
 Standby DB Listener Port Number - Optional\: Port number for the standby database listener. The default is the Oracle default.
 Password File password - Optional\: The password to set in the password file orapw. The default is the Oracle sys Password.
 DB File Name Convert - Optional\: Used only if the primary and standby database datafiles will reside in different locations on the respective servers. Specify an even number of strings\: "string1","string2","string3", "string4",... where string 1 is a sequence of characters in the primary database datafile name, string 2 is a sequence of characters in the first standby database datafile name, string 3 is a sequence of characters in the second primary database datafile name, string 4 is a sequence of characters in the second standby database datafile name, and so on. Each string must be delimited with single or double quotes. For example\: "newyork","chicago","newyork", "atlanta".
 Data Guard Standby Type - Optional\: The type of standby databases that you are configuring. Valid values are Physical, Logical, or Snapshot (only Physical is currently implemented). The default is Physical.
 Update oratab file on Standby Servers - Optional\: Set to Yes to update the oratab file on standby servers. The default is Yes.
 Number of RMAN Primary Channels - Optional\: Number of RMAN (Recovery Manger) primary channels to be used during the RMAN duplicate database process. The default is 2.
 Listener File Location - Optional\: Fully-qualified filename for the listener file. This is only needed for non-standard installs. Do not specify if using the default file $ORACLE_HOME/network/admin/listener.ora or the listener runs from a non-ASM home while ASM is in use.

 Results Verification

The Console will indicate whether the workflow completed without errors. The Output tab will indicate whether the specific Broker operation was successful. 

To further verify the results\:

 1. Set ORACLE_HOME and ORACLE_SID in the terminal(s) on the primary and standby targets.
 2. Log in to SQLPlus\: sqlplus / as sysdba
 3. Run this command\: archive log list;
 4. Compare results to ensure log sequence matches for both databases.



 Additional Documentation

Additional information about HP Database and Middleware Automation is available on HP Live Network\:

"http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation"\:http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation
